Name: Australia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1861 To Dec 1911
Quarterly From Mar 1912 To Mar 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Australian Bureau of Statistics (1861-1920) League of Nations (1920-1945); Australian Bureau of Statistics, Digest of Current Economic Statistics, (1946-)
Notes: Data are annual from 1861 through 1911, and quarterly from 1912 through 1921. Australia only provides a quarterly CPI. No monthly data are available. The CPI (1989/90=100) is designed to provide a general measure of price inflation for the household sector. The index covers price movements of consumer goods and services purchased by all metropolitan private households. This group, which is termed "the CPI population group" includes a wide variety of subgroups, such as wage and salary earners, the self-employed, age pensioners, and social welfare beneficiaries. The current CPI population group represents about 64% of all Australian private households.The cities covered are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Adelaide, Perth, Hobart, Darwin, and Canberra. The CPI is a modified Laspeyres index constructed using the acquisitions approach, which defines the CPI basket as consisting of all those consumer goods and services actually acquired by households during the base period. It is a measure of transaction prices, that is, the prices actually paid by consumers for the goods and services they buy, and is not concerned with recommended, nominal or list prices. The CPI basket is divided into 11 major commodity groups: food; alcohol and tobacco; clothing and footwear; housing; household furnishings, supplies and services; health; transportation; communication; recreation; education and miscellaneous. These groups are divided in turn into 89 expenditure classes. Approximately 100,000 price quotations are collected per quarter from about 4,500 respondents. Prices of most items in the regimen are collected at least once each quarter. Some are collected more frequently and a small number are collected only once a year. The general approach is to price each item as frequently as is necessary to ensure that reliable measures of quarterly price change can be calculated. The majority of items are priced once each quarter, at the same time each quarter, on the assumption that quarterly price movements are adequately represented by movements between two dates three months apart. However, there are some items for which prices generally change by substantial amounts at frequent intervals. In those cases, prices are collected once each month, at the same time each month. Examples where this approach is used are fresh food and new motor vehicles. Finally, a small number of items such as local government rates and charges, whose prices are known to be set once each year are collected annually. The current series was introduced in the September quarter, 2000 (largely based on 1998/99 Household Expenditure Survey data). The index is re-based approximately once every nine years and the weights are revised approximately every five to six years. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Austria Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1863 To Oct 1918
Monthly From Nov 1918 To Jul 2020
Metadata: Sources: Austro-Hungarian data are from Jobst and Scheiber (2014: series AH5A_A). Statistical Office, Statistische Nachrichten, Dec. 1923, p. 195 and subsequent issues (1914-) Notes: Data are semi-annual through 1919, quarterly for 1920, and monthly beginning in 1921. No data are available for April 1938 through December 1943.  Annual data are given for January 1944 through June 1946.  The CPI is for Vienna through March 1959 and for all of Austria starting in April 1959. The VPI (the Austrian CPI) is defined as a fixed base Laspeyres index (2000=100). Prices for 812 commodities are collected in some 4,000 outlets in the 20 largest Austrian cities. The reference day is the Wednesday between the 6th and the 12th of each month. The number of prices collected monthly is 40,000. The number of rent prices collected quarterly, in a separate survey (Mikrozensus), is 15,000.   Weights are derived from a family budget survey, which is carried out every five years, in combination with national accounts data on national household consumption within the economic territory. The latest weight period is 1999/2000.   All published data relate to all Austria. A revision of the CPI basket and the extension of the HICP took place in 2000. The CPI relates to Household Final Monetary Consumption Expenditure (HFMCE) as applied for the HICP in the EU plus the monetary expenditure for investments in the owner occupied house, but not the acquisition of the house itself.  The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Canada Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1761 To Dec 1913
Monthly From Jan 1914 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Source: Dominion Bureau of Statistics, Canada Yearbook, Ottawa: Dominion Bureau of Statistics (1915-1930), League of Nations (1931-1945); Statistics Canada, Canadian Statistical Review (1946-)
Notes: Data from 1762 to 1910 are from Paquet and Wallot (1998: 317-320)
Data are annual for 1910-1914, and quarterly for 1918. All other data are monthly. The Consumer Price Index for Canada (1992=100) measures price changes at the retail level, sales taxes included. The index is a Laspeyres-type index and is constructed as a chain of fixed-basket indices, linked every four years, as a rule. Prices are obtained from special surveys providing, on average, 60,000 monthly price quotes for about 600 representative commodities. The prices are collected in 15 to 76 locations depending on the price behaviors of the specific commodity, from approximately 7,000 outlets, and are collected mostly over the first three weeks of the month. The index covers all provinces of Canada, and the territorial cities of Whitehorse, Yellowknife and Iqaluit. The target population consists of families and individuals living in urban and rural private households. Persons living in collective households and on Indian reserves, officials representing foreign countries, and residents of the Yukon, Northwest Territories and Nunavut outside Whitehorse,Yellowknife and Iqaluit are excluded from the survey. The weights are derived from the 2001 Survey of Household Spending. Weights are generally revised every 4 years and the index is re-based approximately every 10 years. The data for the overall index (All-items), as well as certain more disaggregated indices, are seasonally-adjusted.

Name: Czech Republic Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jul 1914 To Jan 1921
Monthly From Feb 1921 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: League of Nations (1933-1945); United Nations (1946-48); Federal Statistical Office, Monthly Bulletin Notes:  No data available for September through December 1939, July through December 1942, March through September 1944, and August 1948 through December 1962.  Data are quarterly from 1963 through June 1994. Data are disseminated on the Consumer Price Index (two base years: December 1999=100 and Average 2000=100), a modified Laspeyres index. The index that takes average 1995=100 is also calculated. The index covers the entire country, both urban and rural areas.  Since 2001, the CPI has covered some 790 selected representative items.  Approximately 90,000 price quotes are collected from about 10,000 selected shops. Every representative item is surveyed at 1-16 shops, according to the size of a municipality, and in total. Prices are collected once a month, between the 1st and the 20th calendar day of the reference month, and include taxes.   The weights are based on household expenditures as measured by family budget statistics for 1999. Indices are compiled for the aggregate CPI (households in total), as well as for the following indices: households of employees; households of pensioners; low income households with children and households living in Prague. The weights for the aggregate CPI are based on the structure of the average expenditures for all households. The weights for the other CPI are based on the structure of expenditures of a given social or regional group of households.  A comprehensive revision of the indices is made approximately every 5 years. At the time of the last revision in 2000, the sample of price items, the sample of shops, and the weighting pattern were revised, and a breakdown according to COICOP was introduced. At the same time, the base year of the index was changed to December 1999.   The main CPI data are not seasonally adjusted, but the aggregate data published are seasonally adjusted with CPI (preceding month = 100).

Periodicity:

Metadata:
Sources: B. R. Mitchell, European Historical Statistics, 1750-1975, New York: Facts on File, 1980 (1815-1914), Statistiske Department, Statistisk Arbog, Copenhagen: Statistiske Dept. (1914-1920), League of Nations (1921-1945); Statistiske Department, Statistiske Efterretninger (1946-)
Notes: Data from 1502 to 1876 are from Abildgren (2009: 23-25; 2010: Data for Essay 10, 10.2 spreadsheet). Data are annual for 1876 through 1914, semi-annual for 1914-1926, quarterly 1927-1966, and monthly beginning in 1967. The CPI is a Laspeyres-type index (weight base = 1999, prices = 100 in 2000). The weights are based on a 1999 household budget survey combined with the weights of the consumer groups in the national accounts. Prices are collected monthly or with less frequency for particular goods and services whose prices are known to change less frequently. using a stratified sample of the whole country. 25,000 prices are collected every month in approximately 2,000 outlets.

The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Finland Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jul 1913 To Jan 1920
Monthly From Feb 1920 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: League of Nations (1920-1945); Central Statistical Office, Bulletin of Statistics (1946-) Notes: Data are disseminated on the consumer price index, a fixed base Laspeyres index (2000=100). The index covers the final household monetary consumption expenditure in the territory of Finland. The geographic coverage is the  whole country and all socio-economic groups. The index covers explicitly some 700 sub-categories (products) for which about 50,000 price observations are collected every month. In addition to CPI data collection, data from systems of house price- and rental statistics are used as a part of the CPI as well.  The index weights have been derived from the National Accounts. The CPI is re-based every 5 years. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Germany Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1325 To Dec 1869
Monthly From Jan 1870 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: B. R. Mitchell, European Historical Statistics, 1750-1975, New York: Facts on File, 1980 (1820-1912), Richard Calwer, Monatliche Ubersichten uber Lebensmittelpreise, Berlin, (1913-1919), League of Nations (1920-1945); Bayerischen Statistician Landesamt, Bayern in Zahlen, Munchen: Bayerisches Statistisches Landesamt (1945-1948) Bundesamt, Wirtschaft und Statistik (1948-) Notes: Data are annual for 1820 to 1869.  Germany's official CPI began in February 1920, but prior to that a consumer price index calculated by Gielen is used. Also available is an index of the average level of foodstuff prices in 200 German cities is available (in CPDEUCFM).  See Richard Calwer, Monatliche Ubersichten uber Lebensmittelpreise, Berlin, 1913ff., as cited in Gerhard Bry, Wages in Germany 1871-1945, Princeton, 1960) 440-445. The base is July 1914 = 100.   Prices stabilized in December 1923, and a new series in gold Reichsmark was introduced.  The series are allowed to overlap for comparison.  The official German CPI series continued until February 1945 when it was halted.  The data for March 1945 through June 1948 is from Munich where a CPI index used the old 1913/14=100 gold marks base.  In July 1948 the Bundesamt once again began calculating an official CPI Index for the entire country, and this index is used currently.   Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres price index (2000=100) which covers all population groups and all regions of the Federal Republic of Germany.The index is updated by collecting a sample of approximately 350,000 prices for approximately 750 commodities, collected from approximately 40,000 retail outlets in 190 municipalities throughout Germany. The prices are collected in the middle of the month.  The weights used in the index are based on surveys of household expenditure on goods and services, and are revised at five-yearly intervals. The next price base year of the index will be 2005. ne consumer price index is computed for Germany overall. In addition, consumer price indices are available for many federal states. Since January 1997, price changes are also measured monthly by the HICP (Harmonized Index of Consumer Prices) which is computed for European purposes.

Name: Greece Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1914 To Oct 1922
Monthly From Nov 1922 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: League of Nations (1920-1939); G. Delivanis and W. C. Cleveland, Greek Monetary Developments, Bloomington: Univ. Of Indiana Press (1939-1946); National Statistical Service, Monthly Statistical Bulletin (1946-) Notes: The data are rebased beginning in 1946 to reflect the end of the inter-war hyperinflation. Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres-type index (1999=100), which covers the entire country of Greece. The Greek CPI is a fixed base index, revised at approximately 6-year intervals. The weights of the items (good and services), which are used for the compilation of the revised CPI, were calculated on the basis of the results of the Household Budget Survey conducted in the period October1998 - November 1999. In the frame of the last revision of the Index, its geographic coverage was extended from the urban areas to the whole country.   The Population coverage is the same as that of the previous CPIs. More precisely, the index covers, as regards the weights, private households only, leaving out collective households and foreign visitors (tourists) in Greece.   Prices are collected from outlets located in 25 cities of Greece, whose markets are considered as representative centers of wider geographic areas. Depending on the items, the outlets are distinguished as department stores, specialized stores, supermarkets, open-air markets and enterprises rendering services. The frequency of price collection varies depending on the nature of the products. Prices of fresh products (fruit and vegetables and fish) and energy products (heating oil, petrol) are collected once a week. For the other products, prices are collected once a month. Weekly prices refer to Tuesday. Monthly prices are collected in a cyclical manner so as to refer to the whole month. The collected prices correspond with the prices actually paid by the consumer and consequently all taxes (included VAT) are included.  The basket covered by the index comprises 725 products from 12 product categories. Monthly price quotations number approximately 50,000 and are collected from 4,500 outlets and 1,500 households. Prices are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Hong Kong Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Quarterly From Mar 1947 To Dec 1950
Monthly From Jan 1951 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Hong Kong Statistical Bureau, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics (1947-) Notes: Data are quarterly from 1947 to 1950 and monthly thereafter. Data are disseminated for four different CPIs, namely, Consumer Price Index (A) [CPI(A)], Consumer Price Index (B) [CPI(B)], Consumer Price Index (C) [CPI(C)] and Composite CPI. (1) The CPI(A) is based on the expenditure patterns of about 50 percent of households, in the relatively low expenditure range, in Hong Kong, which had an average monthly expenditure of $4,500-$18,499 in 1999/2000 (October 1999 - September 2000). (2) The CPI(B) is based on the expenditure patterns of the next 30 percent of households, which had an average monthly expenditure of $18,500-$32,499 in 1999/2000. (3) The CPI(C) is based on the expenditure patterns of the next 10 percent of households, which had an average monthly expenditure of $32,500-$65,999 in 1999/2000.  (4) The Composite CPI, which is the main indicator of consumer price inflation in Hong Kong, is based on the expenditure patterns of all the above households taken together. The CPIs are Laspeyres indices, with a base period of the 12-month period from October 1999 to September 2000. The CPIs cover 984 items. About 45,000 price quotations from some 4,000 outlets, including retail outlets and service providers, are obtained monthly. Prices do not include general sales tax as it does not exist in Hong Kong, but do include duties imposed on a very confined list of items such as motor spirits, tobacco, and drinks containing methyl alcohol. Prices are collected twice a week, monthly, bi-monthly, quarterly, and annually for different items. The weights are derived from the Household Expenditure Survey, and the indices are re-based and the weights revised every five years. Seasonally adjusted CPIs are also available.

Name: Hungary Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Monthly From Sep 1922 To May 1946
Weekly From Jun 1946 To Dec 1946
Annual From Dec 1947 To Dec 1957
Monthly From Jan 1958 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Base: 1929 = 100 for the pre-World War II data
Sources: League of Nations (1922-1944), Bertrand Nogaro, Hungary Recent Monetary Crisis and Its Theoretical Meaning, American Economic Review 38:4 (1948), pp. 526-542, Central Statistical Office, Monthly Statistical Bulletin (1964-)
Notes: No data are available from February 1944 through June 1945. Data are annual from 1957 through 1963 and monthly from March 1964. Data are disseminated on the CPI, an annual-chained Laspeyres index (December of the previous year=100) covering all households and the entire country.
The index covers 1,100 items. More than 100,000 price quotes are collected each month from approximately 8,000 outlets. (The number of price quotations for each item varies from 30 to 150, depending on its character.) Prices are collected once a month within a given 3 week period.
The weights are derived from the latest household budget survey. Underreporting of expenditure on certain items such as alcohol and tobacco are corrected using macro data of the National Accounts. The reference base for the weights is two years prior to the current year (for example, in 2002 the weights are based on the expenditure structure of 2000). The representative items, outlets, and weights are revised annually. The consumer price indices and the underlying inflation data are seasonally adjusted.

Name: India Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate - Combined
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Jul 1920
Monthly From Aug 1920 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Department of Statistics, Commercial Intelligence Department. Prices and Wages in India. Calcutta: Superintendent of Government Printing, 1923 (1870-1916); Department of Commercial Intelligence and Statistics. Index Numbers of Indian Prices. Calcutta, 1928 (1916-1920); League of Nations (1920-1945); Reserve Bank of India, Monthly Bulletin (1946-) Notes: Data before 1920 are annual from the sources via Williamson. Data are a weighted average of consumer prices, especially for grain from Dacca, Agra, Cawnpore, Delhi, Bombay, Ahmedabad, Secunderabad, Madras and Banglore. Official monthly data begin in 1920. Data are disseminated for 3 separate consumer price indices: (1) the Consumer Price Index for Industrial Workers (CPI [IW]); (2) the Consumer Price Index for Rural Labourers (CPI [RL]) and (3) the Consumer Price Index for Urban Non-Manual Employees (CPI [UNME]). (1) The Consumer Price Index for Industrial Workers (CPI [IW]), 1982=100, is a Laspeyres index covering industrial workers' families in 70 industrial centers throughout the country. The population covered by these 70 industrial centers is approximately 20 percent of the total population of India.  The index covers 260 items, and approximately 160,000 retail price quotes are obtained each month from 16,545 outlets and selected open markets. About 81 percent of the price quotes are collected every week for price sensitive items. Prices for some commodities (about 18 percent of the price quotes) are collected on a monthly basis. Prices of items such as house rent, school or college fees and school/college books (about 1 percent of the price quotes) are collected every six months. The price quotes include all taxes.  The weights for the present series are based on the results of the Family Income and Expenditure Survey conducted during the period from March 1981 to July 1982 in all 70 centers. The index is re-based once every ten years. Generally, efforts are made to update the weights every 10 years by conducting a fresh WCFIES. However, due to various reasons, this schedule could not be adhered to. The latest update of the CPI weights was done in 1981-82, after a gap of 22 years. The data for the CPI (IW) are not seasonally adjusted. (2) The Consumer Price Index for Rural Labourers (CPI [AL/RL]), 1986-87=100 is compiled for 20 States and for All-India. An index is also compiled for agricultural labour households, which is a subset of the rural labour households. The States indices are Laspeyres indices. The All-India index is compiled as the weighted average of the 20 State indices, based on the estimated consumption expenditure of all rural and agricultural households in each States as a proportion of total consumption expenditure for All-India.  The indices for each State covers 85 to 106 items, and 61,005 retail price quotes are collected once a month from selected shops in selected markets serving 600 fixed sample villages, spread over 66 zones and 20 states. The collection of retail prices is staggered over the four weeks of a month, with one quarter of the sample villages being covered every week on a fixed collection day. The price quotes include all taxes.  The weights are based on the consumer expenditure data obtained from the central samples collected by the National Sample Survey Organization (NSSO) during the 38th round conducted in 1983. The weighting diagram of the CPI (RL) covers the rural labour in 20 major states, which represent 99.5 percent of the total labour households in the country.  The previous base of the index was 1960-61=100, and the index for that series covered only agricultural labourers.  The data for the CPI (AL/RL) are not seasonally adjusted. (3) The Consumer Price Index for Urban Non-Manual Employees (CPI [UNME]), 1984-85=100, is a Laspeyres index covering the non-manual population in 59 selected urban centers throughout the country, which represent approximately 40 percent of the total urban population of India. The index covers an average of approximately 250 items, although the number of items of goods and services varies from center to center. (The smallest number of items covered by the index [146] is in Imphal, and the largest number of items [345] is in Delhi.) 1,022 price quotes are collected once a month from approximately 1,022 outlets. The prices include taxes.  The weights of the present series are based on the results of the Family Living Survey, conducted during the period 1982-83 in 59 selected urban centers through the country. Market surveys were also carried out during 1983 in each of the 59 centers preparatory to regular price collection. Data using the 1984-85 base has been disseminated since November 1987. There is no fixed schedule for re-basing the index. The previous base year was 1960. The data for the CPI (UNME) are not seasonally adjusted.The CPI for Industrial Workers is used through 2010.  Beginning in 2011, the Combined CPI for Rural and City consumers is used.

Name: Indonesia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jul 1926 To Dec 1928
Monthly From Jan 1929 To Jan 1935
Quarterly From Apr 1935 To Sep 1936
Monthly From Oct 1936 To Feb 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Jeffrey G. Williamson (1830-1940); Central Bureau of Statistics, Indicator Ekonomi (1948-)
Notes: Pre-World War II and Post World War II indices are not comparable.
Williamson calculated a monthly average of prices for different consumer goods based upon rice, imported textiles, cooking oil and sugar prices. Data are annual. There is no link between the pre-war and post-war indices. No monthly data are available from July 1964 through March 1966 and annual data have been inserted.
Data are disseminated on the Consumer Price Index (2002=100), a modified Laspeyres index covering 45 major urban areas throughout Indonesia.
The index covers between 283 and 397 goods and services classified into seven major groups: food; prepared food, drinks, cigarettes, and tobacco; housing; clothing; education; health; and transport and communication. Each group consists of several subgroups of items, and in addition, some items have several levels of quality or specifications. Prices include sales taxes and are collected each Tuesday for food, clothing, and kerosene items and monthly (on the Tuesday closest to the 15th) for most remaining items.
The weights used in the index are based on the 2002 Cost of Living Survey (CLS) which covered 70,000 households in 45 cities (30 provincial capital cities, and 15 major cities) throughout Indonesia. The index is re-based and the weights are revised approximately every 5 years. The index will be re-based and the weights will be revised according to the 2007 Cost of Living Survey (CLS). The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Ireland Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jul 1914 To Mar 1922
Quarterly From Jun 1922 To Dec 1996
Monthly From Jan 1997 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Central Statistical Office, Statistical Bulletin and Statistical Yearbook, Dublin: CSO (1922-) Notes: Data are quarterly through 1961 and monthly thereafter. The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a Laspeyres-type index calculated on the basis of over 50,000 price quotations taken at 82 locations throughout the country to base mid-December 2001=100. 613 items are covered by the index. Prices are collected monthly, quarterly and yearly. The expenditure weights for the index relate to all private households adjusted to include tourist expenditure and are based on the 1999/2000 Household Budget Survey (HBS). Seasonally adjusted data are not disseminated.

Name: Israel Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jan 1922 To Jul 1922
Monthly From Aug 1922 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Palestine Statistical Annual (1922-1938), League of Nations (1939-1945); Israel Central Statistical Bureau, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics (1946-)
Notes: The original base was January 1922 = 100. No data were calculated for February through June 1922. Data are for all of Palestine through 1938, for Jewish market prices starting in 1939 and for Israel itself starting in 1948. No data were available for August through December 1942.
Data are disseminated on the consumer price index, a Laspeyeres index (2000=100) measuring the change in household expenditure necessary to buy a ""basket"" of commodities and services.
The index covers 1,370 goods and services. Each month 40,000-price quotes are obtained from 2,000 outlets and 500 households. Prices for goods (about 60% of the items) are collected on a weekly basis, while those for services are collected on a monthly basis. The prices include all indirect taxes, such as VAT and purchase tax.
The weights used in the index are obtained from the 1998/99 household surveys covering all income groups in urban households (about 90% of the total population).
The base year has changed in past every 5-6 years, when data on the consumer basket are updated on the basis of Household Expenditure Surveys. As of 1997, Household Expenditure Surveys are conducted annually, thus leading to a policy of more frequent updating.
The data for several consumption groups (fresh fruit and vegetables, clothing and footwear, vacations and travel abroad) are seasonally adjusted, and seasonally adjusted indices for these groups are published in addition to the unadjusted indices.

Name: Italy Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1310 To Dec 1919
Monthly From Jan 1920 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: B. R. Mitchell, European Historical Statistics, 1750-1975, New York: Facts on File, 1980 (1861-1919), League of Nations (1920-1945); Central Institute of Statistics, Monthly Bulletin (1946-) Notes: Annual data were used for 1861 through 1919 and from August 1939 through 1943. The Italian consumer price index, (Indice nazionale dei prezzi al consumo per l'intera collettivitÃƒÂ  NIC) is an annually chained Laspeyres type index (reference base period 1995=100) covering the whole national territory. From January 1999, Istat adopted a chain Laspeyres index, re-based yearly, with a price reference period in December of previous year.  Prices are collected monthly with the exception of durables, semi durables and rents (quarterly) and seasonal goods (twice a month). The prices of the reference month are collected from the 16th day of the previous month up to the 15th day of the current month. The price quotations refer to a group of approximately 1,031 products classified accordingly to the COICOP'95 Rev.1 classification. The CPI is based on approximately 332,000 price quotations each month taken at 33,000 sales outlets and 11,000 households.  The weights are represented by the values of final household consumption as derived from the National Accounts. These values are then corrected on the basis of other information derived from the Household Budget Survey and from other sources.  Price changes are also measured monthly by the FOI (CPI for white and blue collars workers) and the HICP index (Harmonized Index of Consumer Prices) with the same methodology. The FOI index (without tobacco) is widely used for indexing purposes in Italian laws and regulations. The HICP index is computed for European purposes. Data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Japan Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1790 To Dec 1921
Monthly From Jan 1922 To Jul 2020
Metadata: Sources: Williamson (1868-1900); League of Nations (1922-1945); Bureau of Statistics, Monthly Statistics of Japan (1946-) Notes: Williamsons cost of living index was constructed from prices in Tokyo for rice, soybeans, and salt (LTES vol. 8: 153-154), and prices of firewood and salted fish (LTES vol. 8: 138-151). The missing years 1894-95 for the price of salt were filled by linear interpolation. The (fixed) weights were derived from consumption budgets for the Ã¢â‚¬Å“typicalÃ¢â‚¬Â family (LTES vol. 8: 138-141 and vol. 6: 136-137).  The weights were: cost of living = (rice).70 + (soy).07 + (salt).01 + (firewood).08 + (salted fish).14.Data are annual for 1900 through 1921 and monthly thereafter. The CPI is calculated as the weighted arithmetic mean with fixed base (Laspeyres formula, 2000 = 100), covers the whole of Japan, excludes ""one-person households"". (The CPI which covers the all households including one-person households is also calculated as a supplementary index.)  The index covers 598 items. The prices of index items are collected in the monthly Retail Price Survey in principle. In this survey, prices are collected in 167 sample cities, towns and villages, selected by using probability sampling method to represent the whole country. The prices are surveyed once a month in principle, but the prices of fresh food and cut flowers are collected three times a month as their prices sharply fluctuate day by day. Approximately 230,000 price quotes are obtained each month from 30,000 establishments and 22,000 rental units. The weights are based on the 2000 Family Income and Expenditure Survey and are revised once every five years. The base year is also changed every five years. Seasonally adjusted indices are also calculated.

Name: Malaysia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1948 To Feb 2020
Metadata: Sources: Department of Statistics, Monthly Statistical Bulletin (1948-) Notes: Data are disseminated on the consumer prices index, a Laspeyres index (2000=100) covering urban and rural areas of Malaysia. The index covers about 430 items. Each month approximately 190,000 price quotes are obtained from about 19,000 retail outlets throughout the country. Prices are collected monthly, except for prices on rental property which are collected on a quarterly basis, and for perishable items, weekly. The weights used in the index are derived from the household expenditure survey conducted in 1998/99. The weights are normally revised every 5 years. The index is normally re-based every 5 years in tandem with the revision of the weights. The data are disseminated in a non-seasonally-adjusted format.

Name: Mexico Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1886 To Dec 1933
Monthly From Jan 1934 To Dec 1987
Weekly From Jan 1988 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Instituto Nacional de Estadistica Geografia e Informatica, Estadisticas Historicas de Mexico, Mexico City: INEGE (1886-1933), League of Nations (1934-1945); Banco de Mexico, Indicadores Economicos, Mexico: Banco de Mexico (1946-) Notes: Data are annual from 1886 through 1933, and monthly thereafter.  No data are available from 1914 through 1918. Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres index (1994 = 100) covering urban consumers living in towns with more than 20,000 inhabitant. Price information is gathered from 18,400 retail outlets and 8,000 rental housing units, 70,000 prices are gathered each month for 313 generic products and services in 46 Mexican cities. For food items, daily information is obtained; for non-food items, bi-weekly observations are obtained. Data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Netherlands Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1450 To Dec 1918
Monthly From Jan 1919 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: B. R. Mitchell, European Historical Statistics, 1750-1975, New York: Facts on File, 1980 (1880-1918), International Statistics Institute (1919-36), League of Nations (1937-1940); Central Bureau Statistics, Maandschrift (1946-)
Notes: Data are annual from 1880 through 1918. No data were available for August 1944 to June 1945, and annual data were inserted. Quarterly data were used for July 1945 to March 1946. No data were available for October and November 1946 and the datum for December 1946 was inserted into those two months.
Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres index (2000=100) covering all private households in the Netherlands.
The index covers some 90,000 prices collected from about 9,000 outlets each month. There are 127 different outlet types. For each article, the number of observations is spread over the different outlet types according to turnover value. Some 1,000 enterprises regularly receive mail questionnaires. Once a year, about 3,500 landlords receive a rent survey questionnaire. The number of price quotations for an item depends on its weight and price variation.
In addition, scannerdata are collected from some super market chains. These data contain information on sales volumes and average prices paid for all articles, sold in these super markets.
Price data are collected on a monthly basis. In some case, when prices are known to be adjusted only once or a few times per year price collection is in accordance with this. The prices generally refer to the first three working weeks of the month. Fuel prices are collected daily.
For the price observations through scannerdata every month the prices of the first two full weeks enter into the computations.
The weights are derived from primarily from National Accounts results on private consumption. Additional information at a more detailed level is taken from a 2000 Household Budget Survey. This survey measures the set of goods and services which were acquired in the base year from the net spendable income of the average household, for prices which were known to households at the moment of acquisition. Furthermore sales information from some market research bureaus is used to adjust weights at the most detailed level.
The price developments of articles that are sold in supermarkets are a weighted average of the scannerdata results in the super markets supplying these data, and the prices from measurements by interviewers in other outlets. The index is rebased at 5-yearly intervals up to 2000. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: New Zealand Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1857 To Jul 1914
Monthly From Aug 1914 To Dec 1920
Quarterly From Mar 1921 To Dec 1933
Monthly From Jan 1934 To Jan 1943
Quarterly From Mar 1943 To Jun 2020
Metadata:
Definition: The indices measure the quarterly changes in the retail sale prices of a constant basket of goods and services. Owner-occupied housing is included.
Coverage: Expenditures of all New Zealand residents living in private households except those in remote areas are covered.
Collection: Prices are collected weekly, monthly, quarterly or annually depending on the expected frequency of price changes exhibited by the good or service. They are collected in 15 urban/suburban areas for 352 items. Owner-occupied housing is measured using changes in house prices under an acquisitions approach.
Calculation: The indices are calculated using the Laspeyres formula with expenditure weights derived from the 1997/98 Household Economic Survey (HES) and a range of industry sources updated to reflect June 1999 quarter prices. Sources: New Zealand Department of Statistics, Monthly Abstract of Statistics, Wellington (1914-)
Notes: Data are quarterly from 1921 to 1933, monthly from 1934 to 1942 and quarterly again, starting in 1943.

Name: Norway Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1516 To Dec 1919
Monthly From Jan 1920 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Grytten, O.H.(2004). ""A consumer price index for Norway 1516-2003"", 47-98, Historical Monetary Statistics for Norway 1819-2003, Norges Bank Occasional Papers no. 35, Oslo, 2004, Central Statistical Office, Manedshefte and Bank of Norway, Economic Bulletin (1946-)
Notes: Data are annual through 1919, and monthly beginning in March 1920. The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a chained Laspeyres index (1998=100) covering all private households and their purchase of goods and services for household consumption. Data from 1777 to 1920 are taken from Jan Tore Klavland, Contributions to a history of prices in Norway: Monthly Price Indices, Norges Bank Bicentenary Project Working Paper. The TPI index is used.
The index covers approximately 900 representative consumer goods and services. Approximately 40,000 - 45,000 price quotes are obtained each month from a sample of about 2,000 retailers, with one sixth of the sample being replaced each year. The prices are collected once a month on the 15th of each month.
The weights used in the index are derived from the annual household expenditure surveys (using a moving average of the last three annual surveys available) and annual retail trade statistics at the branch level.
The seasonally-adjusted data for the total CPI are published in the Dagens Statistikk (Statistics daily) and are also available on request from the contact person above. However, the detailed data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Pakistan Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1949 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Statistics Division, Ministry of Finance, Planning and Economic Affairs, Monthly Statistical Bulletin (1950-) Notes: The consumer price index (CPI) measures changes in the cost for households of buying a representative fixed basket of goods and services.  The consumer price index series are Laspeyres indices (2000-01=100). The series cover 35 urban centers (large, medium, and small) that represent about 68% of the total population.  Indices are published cross classified by four income groups and four occupational categories combined (industrial workers, commercial employees, government employees, self-employed and employers). In addition, data by geographic areas are given. Excluded are defense personnel and households whose main income consists of transfers. Prices for 374 representative items are collected of which the manufacture items are classified according to the Pakistan Standard Industrial Classification. Depending upon the size of the urban centre, 1 to 13 markets have been selected in which prices are collected; the total number of markets covered is 71. For 53 essential items, weekly prices are collected. The prices of other items are collected once a month, but more frequently if large price swings are noted. Four price quotes for each item are recorded through personal visits to the selected outlets. Approximately 106210 price quotes are collected from 35 urban centers covering 71 markets. The collected prices reflect actual transactions and are valued inclusive of taxes. Weights for the indices were derived from the 2000-01 Family Budget Survey, which had a sample size of 42000 households and recorded expenditures over the period of a year (that is, 10000 households were surveyed in each quarter).  The weights of seasonal items that are temporarily not available are deleted from the calculations. Totally new items do not enter the CPI between two base years, except as a replacement for discontinued items. The prices of items missing temporarily are carried forward. If the item is missing for more than two months, a replacement is sought.  Possible quality differences between the original item and its replacement are removed by imputing a base year price for the replacement item. If no replacement item can be found, the weight of the original item is distributed over the other items. Seasonally adjusted data are not published but may be compiled. The FBS also compiles and publishes a Sensitive Price Indicator (SPI) to assess on a weekly basis the short term price movements of 53 essential commodities in 17 major cities.  The SPI is computed for industrial workers, commercial employees and government employees belonging to the lowest income groups.

Name: Peru Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1900 To Dec 1923
Monthly From Jan 1924 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: League of Nations (1913-45), Central Reserve Bank, Bulletin (1946-)
Notes: Data are annual from 1913 to 1923 and monthly thereafter. The consumer price index (CPI), which is compiled by the National Institute of Statistics and Data Processing (INEI), is of the Laspeyres type (December 2001 base=100) and covers metropolitan Lima.
The general index presents eight major groups broken down into 31 groups, 55 subgroups, 163 headings, and 515 varieties. Approximately 40,000 prices are collected each month from 5,000 commercial establishments, including 41 markets, five supermarkets, 500 rented homes, 505 educational centers, and 210 urban and interurban transport lines.
Price data are compiled at various intervals, depending on the type of goods: prices of products sold at retail outlets are collected on Thursdays and Saturdays; prices of products sold at establishments of other types, as well as rent data, are collected once a month. Public utility rate data are updated every time the rates are changed by the provider enterprises.
The weights used to calculate the CPI are derived from the multipurpose national survey (Ã¢â‚¬Å“Encuesta Nacional de PropÃƒÂ³sitos MÃƒÂºltiplesÃ¢â‚¬ÂÃ¢â‚¬”ENAPROM) conducted from October 1993 to September 1994 in Lima. These weights were changed in January 2002 as a result of a revision of the INEI methodology. The main elements of the revision were: an increase in the number of households included in the sample (single-person households and households located at each end of the range of income distribution), the incorporation of 45 new products, and the elimination of 18 outdated items, the updating of the sample of supermarkets and of brands, and the introduction of the geometric mean in the calculation of the indices of heterogeneous varieties.
The revision was aimed at ensuring that the CPI would as far as possible reflect consumption changes over the last seven years. The index base was changed from 1994 to December 2001. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Philippines Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1899 To Mar 1945
Monthly From Apr 1945 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Central Bank of the Philippines, Statistical Bulletin (1937-) Notes: The data are from Williamson from 1899 to 1936 using weights of 91% for rice and 9% for sugar. Data are annual averages for 1937 to 1941.  No data are available from 1942 through February 1945. Data are disseminated on the CPI index (1994=100), which is computed using the weighted arithmetic mean of price relatives, a variant of the Laspeyre's formula with fixed base year period weights.  The index covers between 285 and 771 items, the number varying by province. The survey covers about 9,500 outlets nationwide with about 415,138 price quotations obtained monthly. The criteria for selecting sample outlets are: popularity of an establishment in terms of the line of goods to be priced; consistency and completeness of stock; permanency of outlet; and accessibility of the outlet.  Prices are collected through personal interviews from selected stalls in public markets, sari-sari stores, supermarkets and service shops all over the country. In theNational Capital Region, four price quotations are collected for each sample market for each of the commodity. Price collection for food is carried out weekly in 11 markets. For the non-food commodities, 12 markets are surveyed and the price collection is carried out on the first five days of the month and during the middle of each month. For the provinces, 2 price quotations are collected in the provincial capital, while 4 other price quotations are collected from the municipalities outside the capital during the first five days of the month. However, only 2 price quotations are collected from the provincial capital during the middle of each month. The arithmetic average of these price quotations is used in the computation of the index. The weights for the index are derived from the 1994 Family Income and Expenditures (FIES) data. There is no fixed interval for rebasing the index - so far, the CPI has used 1966, 1972, 1978, 1988 and 1994 as its base years. Rebasing also depends on the availability of the Family Income and Expenditures (FIES) data, used as the index weights. Official data with 1994 as the base year was released in May 1998. Rebasing of the CPI to 2000 is now ongoing.  A seasonally adjusted series is released five days after the release of the original series.

Name: Poland Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jul 1914 To Jan 1921
Monthly From Feb 1921 To Jul 1939
Annual From Dec 1949 To Jun 1962
Quarterly From Sep 1962 To Dec 1982
Monthly From Jan 1983 To Feb 2020
Metadata:
Base: 1929 = 100 for the pre-war data Sources: ISS (1919-1936), League of Nations (1937-1939), National Bank of Poland, Information Bulletin (1983-)

Notes: No data are available from 1940 through 1982. CPI, which is a Laspeyres type of index is calculated using the data gathered from 307 research regions (i.e., a town or a part of the large city) all over the country.

The prices of 1,800 consumer goods and services are surveyed between the first and the 25th day of each month in about 28,000 outlets. Fruit and vegetables are priced three times per month. Prices of the other goods and services are collected once a month. About 500,000 individual price levels are registered each month.

Indices are disseminated with 1998 as a weight reference period. In addition, the indices are also published for the following reference periods: December of previous year; previous month; and corresponding period of previous year.
Since 1990, the weight system has been based on a household budget survey. The weights are revised every year. For fruit and vegetables seasonal monthly varying weights are applied, but for the rest of COICOP categories Ã¢â‚¬“ fixed annual weights. Data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Portugal Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1930 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: League of Nations (1930-45), National Institute of Statistics, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics (1946-).
Notes: Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres chained index (2002 = 100) which covers the entire country of Portugal. The basket covered by the index comprises of 812 products, which are grouped into 12 product categories. 99,000 prices are collected during the last complete week of the month from approximately 12,700 retail outlets. The prices are collected once during the reference week, and include sales taxes and VAT. Prices for fruits, vegetables and fish are collected more frequently (three times a month).
The present series commenced at the beginning of 2003 (with the January CPI) and replaced the previous series based on 1997. The weights used in the index are derived from the household budget survey carried out in year 2000. The household budget survey is based on a sample of approximately 10,000 households and is carried out about every five years.
Major revisions are made every five years. In the interim period the weights are revised every year using data from national accounts and other sources. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Singapore Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1948 To Jul 2020
Metadata: Sources: Department of Statistics, Monthly Digest of Statistics (1948-) Notes: For data prior to 1962, the Malaysian CPI is used since it was calculated in Singapore. Data are disseminated on the CPI (November 1997 - October 1998 =100) which is compiled using a fixed-weight Laspeyres formula.  The index covers 741 items, divided into 7 groups and 138 sections. 33,400 price quotations are collected each month from 2,410 outlets. For perishable food items at wet markets, prices are collected three times a week. Price data on most other items are monitored monthly, usually on the 15th, while those on rentals are obtained on a quarterly basis. The prices are the normal retail prices paid by consumers, including taxes. The weights for the current index series are derived from the results of the Household Expenditure Survey conducted between November 1997 and October 1998. The records of 5,487 households, which comprised the central 90 per cent in the distribution of households by household expenditure, were used to derive the weighting pattern. The weighting pattern and basket of goods and services are revised once every five years to reflect changes in the consumption expenditure pattern of Singaporean households. The CPI is re-based every five years. Seasonally-adjusted indices are published at the group level.

Name: South Korea Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1948 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Mizoguchi, Toshiyuki. Ã¢â‚¬Å“Consumer Prices and Real Wages in Taiwan and Korea under Japanese Rule,Ã¢â‚¬Â Hitotsubashi Journal of Economics, vol. 13, January 1972, 40-56; Bank of Korea, Monthly Statistical Bulletin (1948-) Notes: Prewar data are from Mizoguchi via Williamson. No link is available between the pre-war and post-war indices. No data were available for November 1949 through June 1951 and annual data have been inserted. No CPI was calculated from April 1950 to May 1951.Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres index (2000=100) covering 36 cities which include 82 percent of the total urban population of Korea. (The data exclude the population engaged in farming and fishing and one-person households.)  The index covers 516 items. Prices are collected three times a month for agricultural and marine products, monthly for other goods and services, and quarterly for school fees. Sales taxes are included. The CPI is compiled for each of the price collection dates and the monthly index is compiled by averaging these indices. Approximately 80,000 price quotes are obtained each month from 13,000 outlets, and the quotes are obtained by personal interview.  The weights are derived from the 2000 Family Income and Expenditure Survey. The index is re-based and the weights are changed at five-yearly intervals. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Spain Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1800 To Dec 1920
Monthly From Jan 1921 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Statistisches Reichsamt, Statistisches Jahrbuch fur das Deutsche Reich, Berlin: Statistisches Reichsamt (1921-1929), League of Nations (1930-1945); National Statistical Institute, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics (1946-) Notes: data from 1800 to 1920 are from Estadisticas Historicas Siglos XIX-XX, p. 1289-1290, cuadro. 16.19. Data are annual for 1914 through 1920, 1925 and 1927-1929.  No data are available for August 1936 through September 1939.  Data were also unavailable for January through June 1946 and the datum for July 1946 was used for these months. Data are disseminated on the Consumer Price Index, a annually chained Laspeyres index (2001= 100). The index covers goods and services selected for the purpose of representing household consumption. The year 2001 is the new base and weighting year. The weights of the products are based on the Household Budget Continuous Survey (HBCS). The 484 items chosen are classified according to the COICOP (Classification Of Individual Consumption by Purpose) in 12 groups, 37 sub-groups, 80 classes and 117 sub-classes.   Approximately 200,000 prices are recorded each month (from the 1st to the 22nd) from more than 30,000 establishments spread over 141 municipalities throughout the country. Prices are generally collected once a month at each establishment, except for perishable items which are collected three times a month from all establishments. Indices for seasonal goods: fruits and vegetables, are obtained by moving averages. The data are not seasonally adjusted.  Methodological changes in the CPI calculation have been introduced, from the January 2002 index, to improve and modernise it. The new aggregation formula, the annually chained Laspeyres index, will permit every year to review the list of goods and services and to update the weights of them.

Name: Sweden Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate

Annual From Dec 1290 To Dec 1915
Monthly From Jan 1916 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Data from 1290 to 1830 are taken from Rodney Edvinsson and Johan Soederberg, Consumer Price Index for Sweden 1290 to 2006 (http://www.riksbank.se/templates/Page.aspx?id=26813). Data from 1830 on are from Statistics Sweden.

Name: Switzerland Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1813 To Dec 1919
Monthly From Jan 1920 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: B. R. Mitchell, European Historical Statistics, 1750-1975, New York: Facts on File, 1980 (1890-1919), Statistischen Bureau, Statistisches Jahrbuch der Schweiz, Bern: Verlag des Ar. Institut Orell Fussli (1920-1961); Switzerland National Bank, Statistisches Monatsheft (1962-) Notes: Data are annual for 1890 through 1919 and monthly thereafter. Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres Index covering the entire country. In May 2000 the CPI was put on a new footing (May 2000=100). The new index covers around 1050 survey positions. On average, some 40000 prices are collected each month, from around 3000 sale outlets in 16 regions nationwide (town with built-up areas). Food, fuel and gasoline prices are collected once a month during the first 6 days of the month. Other prices are collected on a quarterly basis. The weights are based on the 1998 Income and Consumption Survey. The new CPI 2000 has been designed as a chain relative index reweighted annually. The first reweighting is scheduled for December 2001.

Name: Taiwan Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1897 To Jun 1951
Monthly From Jul 1951 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: Mizoguchi, Toshiyuki. Ã¢â‚¬Å“Compiling the Long-term Statistics Database for Taiwan,Ã¢â‚¬Â Asian Historical Statistics Project. vol. 1, February 1996, pp. 4-6; Taiwan Central Bank, Financial Statistics Monthly (1951-) Notes: Pre-war data are taken from Mizoguchi. There is no link between the pre-war and post-war data. No international agencies have carried data for Taiwan since the People's Republic of China joined the UN in 1972; however, Taiwan publishes a statistical monthly which contains relevant economic data which is available in most libraries and the data are available over the internet.

Name: Thailand Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1948 To Feb 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Bank of Thailand, Monthly Bulletin (1946-)
Notes: The pre-war index was calculated by Williamson based upon the price for rice and white and grey shirting prices. Data are disseminated on the consumer prices index (1998=100), which is compiled according to the Laspeyres formula.
The index is nationwide and measures changes in the public daily-life purchasing power in urban areas. The representative consumption basket comprises 326 items. Approximately 65,000 prices are collected from a total of 1,535 establishments. (25 establishments in each of 17 markets in the Bangkok Metropolitan area [14 in Bangkok and 3 in adjacent provinces] and 30 establishments in each of 37 markets in other urban areas, each in a different province.)
The frequency of the price collections depends on the type of product, with those for which prices fluctuate being surveyed more frequently. Fresh food, rice, meat, eggs, fish, marine products, fruits and vegetables, and petroleum products (a total of 90 items) are surveyed weekly. Other consumer products, such as beverages, processed food, medicine, household utilities, clothes, personal service fees, footwear and rents (a total of 236 items) are surveyed monthly. The prices measured include VAT and excise taxes.
The weights are based on a Household Expenditure Survey conducted by the NSO in 1998. The index is normally re-based every four years. The re-basing to the 1998 base year was carried out in January 2002. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Turkey Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1469 To Dec 1929
Monthly From Jan 1930 To Feb 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Data from 1469 to 1918 are from Pamuk (2010: Table 1.1). The annual data before 1930 are from Williamson based upon data from D. Quataert, ""Ottoman Reform and Agriculture in Anatolia, 1876-1908"" (unpublished Ph.D. dissertation, University of California, Los Angeles, 1973, pp. 367-70). There is no link between the pre-war and post-war data series. Monthly data are taken from League of Nations (1930-45), State Institute of Statistics, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics (1946-)
Notes: Data are disseminated on the CPI, a Laspeyres Index (2003=100) covering 26 regions and 81 cities throughout Turkey. The index covers 423 items. Approximately 129,940 price quotes are obtained each month from 18,595 outlets in 26 regions and 81 cities. Prices are collected twice each month (four times each month for vegetables and fruits) .The prices include any relevant taxes. The items included in the index and the weights are derived from the 2003 Household Budget Survey. Weights and item basket are updated every year by means of contunious household budget surveys. Separate indices are calculated for Turkey as a whole and for 26 territorial units for statistics (NUTS-1). The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: United States BLS Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate NSA
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1789 To Dec 1874
Monthly From Jan 1875 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: U.S. Government, Statistical Abstract of the United States (1820-1874), Carl Snyder, "A New Index of the General Price Level from 1875," Journal of the American Statistical Association (June 1924); Bureau of Labor Statistics (1913-). See also David, Paul A. and Solar, Peter, "A Bicentenary Contribution to the History of the Cost of Living in America," Research in Economic History (1977), pp. 1-80.
Notes: This index is based a combination of four indices. David and Solar are used from 1789 to 1820. From 1820 through 1874, the annual cost-of-living index calculated by the Federal Reserve Bank is used. From 1875 until 1912, it uses a monthly Index of General Prices calculated by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, which was weighted between wholesale commodity prices (20%) Wage payments (35%), the Cost of Living (35%) and Rents (10%). From 1913 on, the Bureau of Labor's Consumer Price Index is used. For information on how the prices of individual goods have changed, see Scott Derks, ed., The Value of a Dollar, Lakeville, CT: Grey House Publishing, 1999.
The Consumer Price Index (CPI), 1982-84=100, is calculated on the basis of a market basket of 305 entry level items representing all goods and services purchased for everyday living by all residents in urban areas. These residents include about 87 percent of the total civilian noninstitutional population, including wage earners and clerical workers, professional, managerial, and technical workers, short-term workers, the self-employed, the unemployed, retirees, and others not in the labor force.
For most item categories, representing approximately 61 percent of the total expenditure weight, basic indexes are compiled using a geometric mean formula. For the remaining item categories, basis indexes are computed using a modified Laspeyres methodology
Each month 80,000 price quotations are obtained from approximately 23,000 outlets. About 50,000 housing units are contacted to collected data on rents. Prices are usually collected during the first 18 working days (Monday-Friday) of the month. Food, rent, utilities, and some other items are priced monthly in all urban areas. Most other items are priced monthly in three large urban areas, and every second month in other areas. Most pricing is conducted by personal interview; some pricing takes place by telephone. The prices include any applicable taxes, discounts and rebates.
The weights for the CPI are derived from the Consumer Expenditure Surveys for 1993-95, and the average for those 3 years. Historically weights have been revised once every 10 years; however, starting in 2002, weights will be revised every other year. Seasonally adjusted indices are also published.

Name: United Kingdom Retail Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1209 To Dec 1913
Monthly From Jan 1914 To Aug 2020
Metadata: Sources: E. H. Phelps Brown and Sheila V. Hopkins, "Builders' Wage-rates, Prices and Population: Some Further Evidence," Economica (February 1959): 18-37; and E. H. Phelps Brown and Sheila V. Hopkins, "Seven Centuries of the Price of Consumables, compared with Builders' Wage-rates," Economica (November 1956): 296-314; and E. H. Phelps Brown and Sheila V. Hopkins, "Wage-rates and Prices: Evidence for Population Pressure in the Sixteenth Century," Economica (November 1957): 289-306; Central Statistical Office, Annual Abstract of Statistics, London: CSO and Monthly Digest of Statistics (1915-1920) See also  Statistics website: http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/cpi/consumer-price-indices/1750---2003/composite-consumer-price-index-with-description-and-assessment-of-source-data.pdf from 1750 on.Notes: Data from before 1900 are taken from Brown and Hopkins. Annual data are used through 1914 with monthly food prices used for August through December 1914.  Monthly consumer prices begin in January 1915. Data are disseminated on the Consumer Prices Index (CPI), an annually chain linked Laspeyres index (1996=100), which measures the average change in the prices of consumer goods and services in the United Kingdom. The expenditure on which the CPI is based covers all private UK households, foreign visitors to the UK and residents of institutional households. The Retail Price Index is used from January 1947 to date. Prior to 10 December 2003, the CPI was published in the UK as the Harmonised Index of Consumer Prices (HICP). The CPI is the main domestic measure of UK inflation for macroeconomic purposes. The index is compiled using a large and representative sample of more than 650 goods and services for which price movements are regularly measured in about 20,000 outlets in around 150 areas throughout the country. Some 120,000 separate price quotations are used each month in compiling the index.Domestic prices are collected by the private sector company Research International. Prices are collected on the second or third Tuesday of each month, although for some items prices are collected a day on either side of that day. In addition, data are collected by ONS staff from some major suppliers. Prices include taxes such as Value Added Tax (VAT) and insurance tax, as well as duties, including air passenger duty.The item weights used in the CPI are derived largely from the annual UK Expenditure and Food Survey (EFS). Weights for higher level CPI aggregates are derived from Household Final Consumption Expenditure (HHFCE) data from the UK's national accounts. All weights are updated each year, with the basket of goods and services also revised each year. CPI item weights potentially change twice in a year, through changes to COICOP class weights each January and through the introduction of new items in February. The published CPI, and its components, expresses price levels at a given time as a percentage of the level at some previous date, known as the reference date. This date is currently 1996. The reference date for the CPI has never changed. The index is not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Venezuela Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1900 To Dec 1938
Monthly From Jan 1939 To Dec 2019
Metadata: Sources: Central Bank, Monthly Bulletin (1946-) Notes: Data are annual from 1913 to 1938. The index is based upon food prices through June 1953 and a CPI starting in July 1953.  No data were available for October and December 1939. The consumer price index (CPI) for the Caracas Metropolitan Area is produced and disseminated by the Central Bank of Venezuela (BCV). The Caracas Metropolitan Area CPI is a statistical indicator which measures changes in the prices of a basket of goods and services representative of household consumption in the Caracas Metropolitan Area. This measure of price changes is the official measure of price movements in Venezuela and is used in policy decision-making. The National  Statistics Institute (INE) produces and disseminates a national CPI which measures changes in the prices of a basket of goods and services representative of household consumption nationally. Coverage extends to 21 study areas including major cities, regions, and other cities in the rest of the country. At the present time, the INE is in the process of updating the basket, weights, and base year (1997) of its index so that it follows the methodology used by the BCV to calculate the Caracas Metropolitan Area CPI (base 1997).  Since January 2000, the Caracas Metropolitan Area CPI has been published with a new base year 1997=100. The weights are derived from the Family Budget Survey carried out by the institution in the Caracas Metropolitan Area during the period January 1997-March 1998. The index is calculated using the Laspeyres formula. The type of price is the transaction price, collected at 2,000 establishments, with 370 different types of establishment (supermarkets, hypermarkets, convenience stores, open community markets, fast food outlets, and informal shops) for the 287 items making up the basket for the Caracas Metropolitan Area, which represent 93 percent of household final consumption. Name: China Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1978 To Dec 1985
Monthly From Jan 1986 To Jul 2020
Metadata: Definition: The Consumer Price Index (CPI)I measures the change in the level of prices for a specified basket of goods and services normally purchased by urban and rural residents. Coverage: Approximately 226 areas throughout the country are covered, including 80 counties and 146 cities. The primary source of information for the index weights are the urban and rural household surveys that are conducted every five years and cover around 100,000 households, including 40,000 households in urban areas and the remaining in rural areas. The households also complete a diary of purchases for that year. Collection: 251 item-groups have been selected from the household surveys. Each item-group consists of around 2-10 items (certain special item-groups have 15-25 items each). The item-groups are grouped by major categories. In total there are about 600 ""national items"" used for calculating the all-China CPI. The list of items is revised annually for representativeness based on purchases reported in the household surveys. The number of items can change from year to year, but rarely by more than 10 in any given year. Recently, the classification of household expenditures has been revised to bring it closer to COICOP. Prices of perishable items - fruits, vegetables, eggs, poultry, meat and fish - are collected 3 to 5 times every month, and prices of industrial products are collected 1 to 3 times a month. Where prices are still supervised by the government, such as rent, electricity, public transportation, and drinking water the information on such prices is collected once a month. Calculation: The CPI is a composite index that is derived from the urban and rural indices. These indices are aggregated from the basic information at the city and county level. The CPI is an annually-chained Laspeyres price index, which is compiled and disseminated since 2001. Prior to 2001, the index was compiled and disseminated on a month to month and year to year basis using current year weights for most items.  Sources: League of Nations (1926-1945); State Statistical Bureau, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics-China (1946-48); State Statistical Bureau, Monthly Bulletin of Statistics-China Notes: Data are for the cost of living in Shanghai. The monthly CPI with breakdown by 8 categories is disseminated with brief technical commentary in the NBS news release around the 13th of each month. On the following day, further details are provided to the mass media, including aggregate information by urban and rural areas, and by provinces. The data posted on the NBS website are accordingly updated. The first release of the data on annual CPI is in January with the same breakdown as the monthly index. The index is published annually in the NBS publication China Statistical Yearbook with maximum detail including CPI information by sub-categories. Name: Russia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1885 To Jan 1916
Monthly From Feb 1916 To Jun 1930
Annual From Dec 1931 To Jan 1992
Monthly From Feb 1992 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Base: 1914 = 100, January 1927 = 100 Sources: John Parke, Young, European Currency and Finance, Commission on Gold and Silver Inquiry, United States Senate, Serial 9, Vols. 1 and 2, Washington D.C.: Government Printing Office (1916-1924), Raymond Hutchings, Soviet Economic Development, New York: Barnes and Noble, 1971 (1927-1930), Garvy (1974), pp. 316-317, Howard (1976), p. 600, Bank of Russia, Bulletin of Banking Statistics (1992-)

Note: The Pre-World War I and post-World War I indices are not comparable. No data are available from March 1924 to 1926, from 1941 to 1944 and from 1973 to 1991. Data are annual from 1927 to 1972. The Soviet government calculated the data from 1916 to 1924. The data from 1929 to 1955 is based upon the Retail Price Index for State and Cooperative Stores calculated by Garvy, and the data from 1955 to 1972 is a retail price index based upon the turnover tax as calculated by Howard. The current data are calculated based upon monthly changes in consumer prices.

Data are disseminated on the consumer price index, a modified Laspeyres index (1995 = 100), covering all regions of the Russian Federation. The overall index is published, as well as indices for the following three subgroups: foodstuffs, non-food products, and services.

The index includes all major groups of goods and services, covering 500,000 number of prices and tariffs collected from 50,000 commercial organizations. On the 23-25th of each month, prices for 445 goods and services are surveyed in 266 cities from all regions of the Russian Federation. The consumer price includes the value added tax (VAT), excise tax, sales tax, and other indirect taxes.

Data on consumer spending by the population, derived from household budget surveys, are used as weights in the compilation of the CPI. Additional information is also used to determine the specific weight of individual items in the consumer basket: data on the structure of the retail trade turnover, on the output of certain types of products, other sources, and judgments. The weights are derived from the annual household budget surveys of the preceding year and are chain-linked. Weight revisions are introduced in January of each year. There is no fixed schedule for rebasing the index. Data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Slovenia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1951 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Bank of Slovenia, Monthly Bulletin (1992-)
Notes: Data prior to 1992 use Yugoslavian Consumer Prices. Data are disseminated on the Consumer Price Index (CPI), a modified Laspeyres formula which uses each December as the price and index reference period. The CPI measures changes in the level of retail prices of goods and services based on the structure of expenditures of individual residential households intended for final consumption. The index covers the entire Slovenian economy.

The index covers 639 representative items, divided into various sub-headings of COICOP (HICP version) classification. Selected for the basket are products that have the most important share in total consumption and whose changes of prices reflect best changes of prices of related products. Each month approximately 12,000 retail price quotes are obtained from approximately 1,100 outlets in 4 locations (the capital city and three other cities located in the north-east, west, and south of the country). Prices of manufactured products are observed once a month in 3 to 8 trading enterprises. Prices of agricultural products are observed twice a month in 5 trading enterprises and in the open markets. The prices of services are also observed once a month. The prices are inclusive of taxes, and are collected from the 1st to the 25th day of the month.

Weights for calculating the index in a certain year are based on expenditure for household budget surveys as a main data source. These data are supplemented and verified with other statistical and non-statistical sources. In 2004 weights are based on the three-year average of expenditure from surveys in 2000, 2001 and 2002 recalculated (indexed) to the prices of December 2003, which is also the index base month.

The data are disseminated in both original and seasonally adjusted formats. The CPI has been the official measure of the inflation in Slovenia since January 1, 1998. (Prior to that date the Retail Price Index [RPI] was the official inflation measure.)

Name: Slovakia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1963 To Aug 2020
Metadata:
Sources: Slovakia National Bank, Monetary Survey (1993-)
Notes: For data prior to 1993, see the Czech Republic. Data are disseminated on the consumer price index (CPI), a chained Laspeyres index. From January 2005 SO SR starts compilation of the CPI as Laspeyres chained index with annually updated weights. CPI covers approximately 90 % of all households in the Slovak Republic.
From January 2005, after comprehensive revision of CPI consumer prices were collected for the adjusted consumer basket which covered 712 goods and services and about 90,000 price quotations from 8,500 retail outlets. The consumer prices of individual commodities include value-added tax and are collected during the initial 20 days of a reference month.
All general expenditure categories of goods and services, as defined by ESA 95 are covered by the consumer price index. These include: food and non-alcoholic beverages; alcoholic beverages and tobacco; clothing and footwear; housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels; furnishings, household equipment and routine maintenance of the house; health; transport; communication; recreation and culture; education; hotels, cafes and restaurants; miscellaneous goods and services.
The weights are derived from a 2003 household budget survey, adjusted for the results of the 2003 national accounts data. Time series for the years 1990 Ã¢â‚¬“ 2001 were recalculated in breakdown by 12 divisions and 43 groups of the COICOP classification and are available.
The seasonally adjusted consumer price indices of food is published in the monthly publication Consumer Price Indices in the Slovak Republic within 30 days after the end of the reference month.

Name: Estonia Consumer Price Index Inflation Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Jul 1913 To Feb 1924
Monthly From Mar 1924 To Feb 2020
Metadata:
Sources: League of Nations (1924-1940), Estonian Central Bank, Financial Sector Statistics (1992-)
Notes: No data are available from July 1940 through 1991. From 2001, the consumer price index (CPI) data are disseminated on the basis of an annually chain linked Laspeyres index (1997=100). The index covers the whole country and all economic groups except people living in institutions.
The index is compiled using a sample of more than 500 separate goods and services for which price movements are measured in about 1,000 outlets in 10 areas once a month. The CPI is calculated on the basis of approximately 15,000 separate price quotations. The prices include any taxes. The observation period is the week including the 15th of the month.
The weights are derived from the quarterly estimates of the Estonian Family Expenditure Survey; national accounts estimates of private final consumption and administrative information. From 2001, the weights are updated each year. In recent years the index has been re-based and the weights revised in the third quarter of 1990, in June of 1992, in 1993 and 1997.
The index is not seasonally adjusted.
